Cyclone Sidr, a powerful storm with winds up to 240 km/h, hit Bangladesh's coast near the India border.
Evacuations were underway in both countries to save lives.
The storm, visible from space, caused devastation in poor rural areas.
Hundreds died, and thousands were left homeless.
International aid, including from the US and Germany, was mobilized to assist.
The United Nations World Food Program allocated food for 400,000 victims.
Efforts were focused on providing shelter, clean water, and medical aid to those affected.
The priority was to save lives and ensure the well-being of the impacted population.
